   variability, show the regions that historically demonstrate unreliable
   precipitation, and identify the extent of arid regions of the central
   United States based on modeled annual soil moisture variability. We
   asked how arid climates have influenced soil formation patterns at small
   cartographic scales, and how soil properties buffer or enhance soil
   moisture regimes (at the udic-ustic boundary) to climate variability at
   larger cartographic scales. At small cartographic scales, a climate-only
   model worked nearly as well as a climate-and-soils model in mapping the
   region's soil moisture boundary; however, a climate-only model missed
   important local soil influences. Finally, we demonstrate that long-term
   climate and climate variability are reflected in the depth and
   concentration of the calcic soil properties. From a practical
   standpoint, our work highlights that soils with higher water holding
   capacity dampen periodic short-term rainfall deficits, while soils with
